			<title>2024 Law Firm Consumer Reports : PROLOGUE</title>
			<description>&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img src="https://image.lawtimes.co.kr/images/198414.jpg" alt="198414.jpg" style="opacity: 0;" height="10px" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: right;"&gt;&lt;a href="https://ailinggo.ai/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img src="https://image.lawtimes.co.kr/images/lingo2.jpg" alt="lingo2.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;b&gt;1. "The Inception of the 2024 Law Firm Consumer Reports"&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;"On April 25, 2024, the Law Times will debut its inaugural 'Law Firm Consumer Reports' in celebration of 'Law Day'."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The "Law Firm Consumer Reports" title reflects a crucial awareness: previous law firm evaluations by diverse media outlets and organizations often overlooked a significant factor – assessments were not exclusively based on feedback from clients who had directly engaged law firms.&lt;p&gt;To address this challenge, the Law Times undertook a unique approach: conducting a comprehensive survey solely among the legal teams within each affiliate of the top 30 Korean conglomerates and the legal teams of each affiliate of the top 5 financial holding groups. This methodology parallels the direct evaluation process familiar in the restaurant industry, where users assess their dining experiences. By gathering accurate and candid feedback from clients who have directly engaged with law firms, we are confident that the results will offer invaluable insights, benefiting both law firms and companies alike.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The inaugural Law Firm Consumer Reports is driven by a clear vision. Our foremost aim was to authentically capture the vibrant voices of corporate legal staff. We believed that by minimizing processing or editing, we could uphold the objectivity and reliability of this evaluation. Our goal was to forge a credible law firm assessment report acknowledged by the legal market. In Korea, legal consumers invest significant resources in engaging law firms, yet they lack objective information on which cases to entrust to which law firm or lawyer. This information disparity distorts the legal market landscape, prompting our dedication to rectify it. We aspire for the 2024 Law Firm Consumer Reports by the Law Times to stand as the inaugural source of fair and objective information regarding Korean law firms for consumers.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;2. Production Process&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The Law Times has been evaluating law firms every two years since 2014. However, the existing evaluation method had clear limitations. It was challenging to confirm whether the evaluators had actually engaged with the law firm, and there was no way to ascertain the identities of the respondents to the questionnaire. To address these shortcomings, in April 2023, the Law Times established a task force (TF) dedicated to redesigning the overall evaluation process for law firms. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;After three months of internal deliberation, we crafted an evaluation questionnaire comprising three sections. The first section involves competency assessment for each law firm. Respondents are presented with a multiple-choice format, where they select the law firm they engaged with and rate it across 14 criteria, including skills and expertise, prompt processing, communication skills, satisfaction with performance, and appropriateness of fees.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In the second section, respondents are asked to provide scores in 11 fields, such as financial securities, mergers and acquisitions, and capital markets, based on their experience with the law firm they utilized.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Lastly, respondents are prompted to subjectively choose the best law firm, the law firm that fell short of their expectations, the top-performing lawyer, and the lawyer who did not meet their expectations. They are then invited to articulate the reasons behind their selections.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;After the questionnaire was finalized, we established a Law Firm Evaluation Committee in the first week of November 2023. The committee was chaired by Wang Sang-han, the Dean of Sogang University Law School. Other esteemed members included Kim Young-jong, the head of POSCO Holdings' legal team; Kim Sung-han, the chairman of KICA; and Park Chul-young, the chairman of the In-house Council Forum (holding their respective positions at the time).&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;After supplementing the survey questions based on the committee's advice, we proceeded to engage an external professional development company to create a dedicated webpage for law firm evaluations. The development process spanned approximately two months. Concurrently, we reached out to the legal teams of each affiliate within the 30 largest conglomerates and the 5 major financial holding groups.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We initiated contact by sending official letters requesting their cooperation and participation in the survey. Securing the involvement of each corporate legal team head and obtaining their assistance with the survey proved to be a time-consuming endeavor. However, we were committed to ensuring comprehensive participation and garnering valuable insights from all relevant stakeholders. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;While some firms were eager to participate, others expressed apprehension about evaluating law firms with whom they had longstanding business relationships. In such cases, we engaged in detailed discussions to address their concerns.We emphasized the mutual benefits of rigorous evaluation, stressing that law firms stand to enhance their services through feedback from their primary clients, the corporations. Moreover, we underscored how improvements in legal services could catalyze positive changes within the legal market as a whole. Through these conversations, we sought to cultivate a shared understanding of the importance of transparent evaluation processes in fostering continuous improvement and innovation within the legal industry. Ultimately, our efforts aimed to encourage broad participation and facilitate meaningful contributions to the Law Firm Consumer Reports. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Following this extensive process, the survey commenced on January 10th, 2024, and continued for two months, culminating in the completion of data analysis by March 2024. Subsequently, on the 25th of the same month, the Law Firm Evaluation Committee reconvened to seek guidance on interpreting the survey results. Drawing from these insights, we devised a comprehensive framework for the Law Firm Consumer Report.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;With diligent effort and collaboration, we successfully presented the finalized report to the world within one year, spanning from April 2023 to April 2024. This timeline reflects our commitment to thoroughness, accuracy, and timeliness in delivering valuable insights to the legal community and beyond.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;3. Features&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The hallmark feature of the Law Times's 2024 Law Firm Consumer Report lies in its survey respondents. The survey exclusively targeted individuals overseeing the legal teams of the law firms' actual consumers from the top 30 conglomerates and the 5 major financial holding groups. This deliberate approach was predicated on the belief that these individuals, being frequent users of law firms, possess a unique vantage point from which to offer objective and precise evaluations. By centering the feedback of these key stakeholders, the report aims to provide unparalleled insights into the performance and efficacy of law firms in meeting the needs of their clients.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;To address concerns regarding the authenticity of survey participation and mitigate the risk of contamination from external sources, we implemented stringent measures to ensure reliability and security throughout the evaluation process.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Firstly, a separate survey link was meticulously crafted and distributed to each legal team within every participating company. This tailored approach aimed to verify the identity of respondents and minimize the likelihood of unauthorized access to the survey.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Furthermore, to prevent multiple responses from a single legal team, we implemented a restriction on the answer variable based on the predetermined number of legal team members. If an excessive number of responses were attempted, the system would automatically detect and reject them, safeguarding the integrity of the data. These measures represent the minimum safeguards implemented to uphold the confidentiality and accuracy of the survey responses. By prioritizing reliability and security, we aimed to ensure that the insights gleaned from the evaluation are robust and trustworthy, ultimately enhancing the credibility of the Law Firm Consumer Reports.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;During the two-month survey period, a total of 117 companies from 30 conglomerates and 5 major financial holding groups actively participated. Within these companies, 588 individuals from their respective legal teams responded to the survey.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The Law Times extended invitations to all law firms registered with the Ministry of Justice, totaling 1,519 firms, including prominent ones like Kim &amp; Chang, to undergo evaluation. Notably, legal team members directly selected and evaluated the law firms they had engaged with. Ultimately, 103 law firms received evaluations from the 588 individuals in charge of legal teams across the 117 participating companies. This comprehensive approach ensured a diverse and representative pool of feedback, enriching the insights provided in the Law Firm Consumer Reports.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In the evaluation process, six law firms emerged as particularly noteworthy, garnering over 100 responses each in both competency and field evaluations. These firms, namely Kim &amp; Chang, Lee &amp; Ko, Shin &amp; Kim, Yulchon, Bae, Kim &amp; Lee, and Yoon &amp; Yang, were collectively categorized as "Group 1" for detailed analysis. Subsequently, a second tier of analysis, "Group 2," comprised 10 law firms that received responses from three or more companies and five or more individuals. These firms, including DR &amp; Aju, Dongin, LIN, Minju, Barun, LKB &amp; Partners, Jipyong, Chang-chun, Hankyul, and HwaHyun.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;For the law firms not classified within either Group 1 or Group 2, we conducted a meticulous examination of their competency, field, and subjective evaluations. This comprehensive analysis aimed to uncover any discernible patterns, strengths, or areas for improvement, ensuring a thorough overview of the legal landscape depicted in the Law Firm Consumer Reports.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Regarding the pioneering effort to exclusively involve legal team leaders from major corporations in the law firm evaluation process, Wang Sang-han, chairperson of the law firm evaluation committee, said, "The inaugural Law Firm Consumer Reports will offer legal service consumers more accurate information and incentivize law firms to deliver high-quality service" adding, " "I believe it will present an opportunity for the entire legal field to advance and grow.". Kim Sung-han, a member of the evaluation committee, said, "Indeed, we conducted a precise evaluation without contamination by accurately identifying the evaluators and directly administering surveys to individuals working within the legal teams of large corporations.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img src="https://image.lawtimes.co.kr/images/198414.jpg" alt="198414.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;4. Configuration&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;"In Chapter 1, we conducted an analysis of competency evaluation by topic (item), involving 117 affiliates of the top 30 conglomerates and financial holding groups. A total of 588 legal team members participated in evaluating the capabilities of 103 law firms."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Following consultation with the law firm evaluation committee, we narrowed our focus to 'Group 1' and 'Group 2', as these were deemed to provide meaningful evaluations."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;There are 14 competency evaluation indicators in total. (1) Skills and expertise (2) Prompt processing (3) Strategy-making ability (4) Government affairs capabilities (5) Business sense (6) Communication ability (7) Procedural stability (8) Partner lawyer's degree of work involvement (9) Teamwork (10) Satisfaction with performance (11) Detailed and objective explanation (12) Adequacy of fees (13) Degree of public interest activity (14) Willingness to re-appoint and recommend.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;"In Chapter 1, you can review the scores of each law firm on 14 indicators. However, as each law firm's score is relative, we opted not to rank them in terms of first, second, third, and so on. Since each evaluation group's score is presented as is, it appears desirable to conduct a comparative evaluation."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Chapter 2 presents an evaluation analysis by field of work. Similar to the competency evaluation, the evaluation by field of work was conducted by selecting law firms directly used by the legal professionals of the top 30 groups and financial holding companies. There are a total of 11 evaluation areas, including: (1) IT·TMT, (2) Protection of Personal Information, (3) Fair Trade, (4) International Arbitration, International Trade, (5) Financial Securities, (6) Human Resources and Labor, (7) Mergers and Acquisitions, (8) Capital Markets, (9) Taxation, (10) Serious Accident, and (11) Intellectual Property Rights, etc."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We focused on 'Group 1' and 'Group 2', which we deemed to be meaningful evaluations for Chapter 2 as well. The evaluation scores were described as they are, rather than being ranked, enabling anyone to compare and evaluate."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;"In Chapters 1 and 2, which contain analyses of competency evaluations and evaluations by field, apart from Group 1 and Group 2, a separate group of law firms—those with more than three respondents and scores higher than the average of all law firms—received positive evaluations, despite not meeting the minimum standards (i.e., having evaluations from 3 or more companies and 5 or more individuals). These firms are introduced as Group 3. Through this analysis, readers can discern the preferences of large corporations towards small and medium-sized law firms."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;"Chapter 3 provides a subjective evaluation as it is. This evaluation entails respondents directly describing the best law firm, as well as those that did not meet expectations, along with the best and subpar lawyers. Among the listings, 40 law firms are recognized as the best, while 21 are noted as falling short of expectations. Many respondents provided detailed reasons for their assessments. The Law Firm Consumer Report largely presents verbatim feedback, with some content edited to protect respondent anonymity. We believe that providing feedback as it is can significantly assist law firms in enhancing their legal services."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;"A total of 303 lawyers were selected as the best. Among them, 79 were chosen by more than one respondent. Notably, Kim Sang-min, a lawyer from Bae, Kim &amp; Lee (ranked 37th in the JRTI), was selected as the best lawyer by 10 respondents. We provided detailed explanations as to why he was chosen. Additionally, 28 lawyers were identified as falling short of expectations. Since each of them was selected by only one respondent, it is challenging to conclude whether the issue lies in competence or attitude. Therefore, we opted not to disclose the names of these lawyers while providing detailed reasons for their selection. Maintaining a record of these reasons aims to convey the genuine thoughts of legal consumers to law firms."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;"Chapter 4 reconstructs competency evaluation, evaluation by field, and subjective evaluation, with a focus on 11 law firms that received significant evaluations. This aims to provide legal consumers with a quick overview of the capabilities and main areas of expertise of individual law firms when making their selection. It offers a clear understanding of the strengths and weaknesses of each law firm and provides insight into the thoughts of major corporate legal teams regarding these firms. The 11 law firms featured are: (1) Kim &amp; Chang, (2) Lee &amp; Ko, (3) Bae, Kim &amp; Lee, (4) Yulchon, (5) Shin &amp; Kim, (6) Yoon &amp; Yang, (7) Jipyong, (8) Barun, (9) DR &amp; Aju, (10) Dongin, and (11) LKB &amp; Partners."&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Lastly, we introduced three hidden champions that garnered renewed attention through this evaluation of law firms: LIN, HwaHyun, and Chang-chun. Despite not receiving a large number of responses, these three law firms earned positive reviews from both the companies and the legal teams participating in the evaluation. The significance of evaluating law firms lies not only in ranking the major players but also in uncovering new and formidable firms. Hence, the Law Times highlighted these three hidden champions."&lt;/p&gt;</description>
